The air power was hot enough to ignite a special caseless .22 caliber caseless round. Figure this was an air rifle that loaded and shot .22 caseless ammunition.
The death of this design is when the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms found out Daisy was manufacturing a “firearm”. Without the right permits, Daisy suspended all manufacture of this odd little rifle. Only 19,000 standard and 5,000 presentation rifles were produced before Daisy ceased production

title: For Sale:  Finnish M91 mosin. Civil guard & Finnish army marked. Great condition and accurate shooter.
location: Raleigh, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent: This rifle is a Finnish m91 he’s reciever mosin nagant. Built by Tula in 1905* and used by the Finnish military (SA) and civil guard (~S~). The rifle was built during the Russo-Japanese war, but I doubt it saw service since the war ended in 1905. Being that there is no Finnish capture mark I believe that this rifle was in Finnland when it broke off from the Soviet Union. From what I can tell the stock was replaced sometime in the interwar period, If you look at the butt of the stock in the right light you can see there was the number "66" written in grease pen for some time. Rear sight has been remarked with meters on the right hand side with arshin marked out, as is traditional with Finnish Mosins. The original sling mounts are not shown in the photo but are included. This rifle has the best trigger I’ve ever seen on a stock mosin, and is accurate enough to shoot 1.5 inch groups if you do your part. This rifle is CLEAN of cosmoline and the internals of the bolt have been polished to make the action as smooth as possible you don’t have to hit this one to get the bolt to open and close like with many other mosins. If you have any questions please feel free to ask. Included with this rifle will be a front sight adjustment tool.
